Use ASP.NET Core's **`WebApplicationFactory<T>`** — it hosts your app in-memory and gives you an `HttpClient` without opening a real port. Wire that client into the MCP C# SDK's transport layer.

### Setup

```bash
dotnet add package Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing
dotnet add package ModelContextProtocol  # MCP C# SDK
```

### Example test

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing;
using ModelContextProtocol.Client;
using ModelContextProtocol.Protocol.Transport;

public class McpIntegrationTests : IClassFixture<WebApplicationFactory<Program>>
{
    private readonly WebApplicationFactory<Program> _factory;

    public McpIntegrationTests(WebApplicationFactory<Program> factory)
        => _factory = factory;

    [Fact]
    public async Task Tools_ListAndCall_WorkOverHttp()
    {
        // WebApplicationFactory gives you an HttpClient backed
        // by an in-memory test server — no real port needed.
        var httpClient = _factory.CreateClient();

        // Use SseClientTransport or StreamableHttpClientTransport,
        // passing the factory-provided HttpClient so requests
        // stay in-process.
        var transport = new SseClientTransport(
            new SseClientTransportOptions
            {
                Endpoint = new Uri(httpClient.BaseAddress!, "/mcp/sse"),
                Name = "test-client"
            },
            httpClient          // ← key: reuse the in-memory client
        );

        await using var client = await McpClientFactory.CreateAsync(transport);

        // List tools
        var tools = await client.ListToolsAsync();
        Assert.NotEmpty(tools);

        // Call a tool
        var result = await client.CallToolAsync(
            tools.First().Name,
            new Dictionary<string, object?> { ["input"] = "hello" });

        Assert.False(result.IsError);
    }
}
```

### Key points

| Concept | Detail |
|---|---|
| **No real port** | `WebApplicationFactory` hosts your `Program` in-process |
| **Real HTTP stack** | Middleware, routing, auth — all exercised |
| **Transport reuse** | Pass `CreateClient()` into the SDK transport so traffic stays in-memory |
| **Streamable HTTP** | If your server uses the newer Streamable HTTP transport, swap `SseClientTransport` for `StreamableHttpClientTransport` with the same pattern |

Make sure your `Program` class is accessible to the test project (add `InternalsVisibleTo` or use a `public partial class Program { }` marker in your server's `Program.cs`).
